Level 11->12

1)The file data.txt contains text where all letters have been rotated by 13 positions.
This is called ROT13 (a simple substitution cipher).
Your task: decode it to reveal the password.

Solution:
Step‑by‑Step Approach
Check the file contents

bash
cat data.txt
You’ll see text that looks readable but scrambled (letters shifted).

Decode with tr
The tr command can translate characters. For ROT13:

bash
cat data.txt | tr 'A-Za-z' 'N-ZA-Mn-za-m'
tr 'A-Za-z' 'N-ZA-Mn-za-m' → shifts each letter by 13 places.

Uppercase and lowercase are both handled.

This will print the decoded text.

Get the password
The decoded output is the password for Level 12.

🧠 What You Learn in This Level
ROT13 basics: A simple cipher that rotates letters by 13.

Using tr: A powerful tool to translate or substitute characters.

Pattern recognition: When text looks scrambled but readable, ROT13 is a common trick.

Command chaining: Using cat + tr together to transform file contents.

